In this project, I learned how to retrieve climate-related data from online sources, clean and transform it into usable formats, store it in a relational database, and merge multiple datasets using SQL joins. This process deepened my understanding of how to use Python libraries like SQLite for full-stack data wrangling and analysis.

Several changes were made to the data during the cleaning and transformation phase. First, I renamed inconsistent column headers to make them easier to reference in code. I removed percentage symbols and commas from numerical values to allow for proper type conversion. I filtered out any rows with missing or non-location data (such as “World” or regional aggregates) and standardized location name casing for consistency. In joining datasets, I matched records by location and population, assuming both datasets used the same location naming conventions.
